The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Metro | Security scurry after terror alert
                                                                                                                         3                                                                                      Security scurry after terror alert
          A STAFF REPORTER                              
	Calcutta police have bolstered security at the airport and other vital installations following a terror alert by the Union home ministry on Thursday.        
	In its message to the cops, the ministry warned that Lashkar-e-Toiba had planned to carry out a terror attack in one of the metro cities and hijack an aircraft on Republic Day.        
	The report also mentions that the terrorist outfit might target crowded market places or railway stations.        
	Airport security has been stepped up because of Republic Day. Passengers and their luggage are being screened thoroughly. Entry of visitors was banned sometime back, said a senior security official at the Calcutta airport.        
	Security vigil has been intensified on and around the Maidan.         
	Policeman will keep a watch with night-vision binoculars from seven towers. They will carry long-range rifles, said Jawed Shamim, the joint commissioner of police (headquarters).        
	Commandos would be deployed on Red Road, the venue of the parade. All roads leading to it will be blocked from January 25 midnight.        
	Three thousand additional policemen and Rapid Action Force personnel would be deployed for the parade.                                                                                                                                                           
